Here's the standard approach:

### 1. Define theme resource dictionaries

Create one `ResourceDictionary` per theme (e.g., `LightTheme.xaml`, `DarkTheme.xaml`, `HighContrastTheme.xaml`) with identical keys:

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Repeat for `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` with different color values.

### 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        var existing = mergedDicts.LastOrDefault(d => d is IThemeDictionary);
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        ResourceDictionary newTheme = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new LightTheme(),
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(newTheme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static AppTheme GetSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        return Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var t) ? t : AppTheme.Light;
    }
}
```

> **Tip:** Tag each theme dictionary with a marker interface (`IThemeDictionary`) so you can find and replace it easily. Just have each theme class implement it.

### 3. Apply on startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(ThemeService.GetSavedTheme());
}
```

### 4. Reference theme colors with `DynamicResource`

This is the key — `StaticResource` won't update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" Text="Hello!" />
</ContentPage>
```

### 5. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        ItemsSource="{Binding Themes}"
        SelectedItem="{Binding SelectedTheme}"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged" />
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is AppTheme selected)
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(selected);
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Solution |
|---|---|
| Instant swap | `DynamicResource` + replacing the `MergedDictionary` |
| Persistence | `Preferences.Set/Get` |
| Styles & controls | Define `Style` objects in each theme dictionary using the same `x:Key` |
| Platform chrome | Call `Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark/Light` alongside your swap if you also want the status bar and nav bar to match |
